Demo 5 (Robinson): Single-cell RNA-seq pipeline

based on scater’s and scran’s vignettes
(modified by Anthony Sonrel, Lukas Weber, Stefan Milosavljevic, Almut Lütge, Helena L Crowell and Mark Robinson)

Compiled: June 02, 2022

Introduction

This document demonstrates an analysis pipeline for single-cell RNA-sequencing (scRNA-seq) data. We will use the scran and scater R/Bioconductor packages, together with the 10X Genomics 2700 peripheral blood mononuclear cells (PBMCs) dataset.

scran is a Bioconductor R package to perform low-level analyses of single-cell RNA-seq data, including normalization of cell-specific biases, assignment of cell cycle phase, detection of highly variable and significantly correlated genes, correction of batch effects, identification of marker genes, and other common tasks.

The 10X Genomics 2700 PBMCs dataset was made publicly available by 10X Genomics. It is used in the Seurat example vignettes, and is also available for download from the Satija Lab website.

The examples in this document are modified from the scran and scater vignettes Using scran to analyze single-cell RNA-seq data and Data visualisation methods in scater, respectively. Another popular package in single-cell, which we will not present here given the time constraints, is the Seurat package which also has very good documentation (see Guided Clustering Tutorial).

Single-cell RNA-seq data

This session will show you some aspects of how to analyze scRNAseq data. scRNAseq is a relatively young area of research (first article in 2009) that involves sequencing the transcriptome of each single-cell of a sample.

Like other sequencing pipelines (e.g. DNA sequencing), the raw data returned by the sequencing machine first needs to be processed in progressive steps: quality control, filtering, trimming, alignment, and so on.

Here we will directly load PBMC count data that are generated from sequencing reads using the 10x genomics cellranger processing pipeline (10x genomics is one of the many technologies that perform scRNAseq):

suppressPackageStartupMessages({
  library(scater)
  library(scran)
  library(DropletUtils)
  library(SingleCellExperiment)
  library(SingleR)
  library(celldex)
  library(pheatmap)
})
## Warning: package 'S4Vectors' was built under R version 4.1.3
data_dir <- file.path("..", "data")

# Unzip data
untar(
  tarfile = file.path(data_dir, 
                      "pbmc3k_filtered_gene_bc_matrices.tar.gz"), 
  exdir = data_dir)

# Load data
pbmc.sce <- read10xCounts(samples = file.path(data_dir, 
                                              "filtered_gene_bc_matrices", "hg19"), 
                          col.names = TRUE, )

The SingleCellExperiment object

By loading the data as above we have stored all data necessary to perform downstream analysis in one object called a SingleCellExperiment object. Most importantly, this object contains the count data (also called assay - see below) with per-cell counts for all genes in one matrix, as well as cell-related metadata (e.g., sample, batch, treatment, …) and gene-related metadata (e.g., gene symbol).

The counts assay of pbmc.sce is a “dgcMatrix”, a matrix that efficiently stores sparse matrices (most elements are zeros, represented by dots). You will see in the next sections that we can append multiple assays (e.g., raw counts, log-normalized expression). The genes (rows) are named after their gene identifiers (ENSEMBL IDs) and the cells after a tag chain. These DNA-tags were added during the sequencing protocol to differentiate cells and give them an ‘individual identity’.

Within all assays each column represent another cell and each row another gene. Thus you can find the cell names in the column names and cell-related metadata are stored in the colData while gene names correspond to rownames and gene-related metadata are stored in the rowData. We can use accessor functions to extract the information we need from the SingleCellExperiment object.

Structure of a SingleCellExperiment object. Metadata of the rows (genes) are stored in the rowData (pink) while the metadata of the columns (cells) are stored in colData (yellow).

Library sizes and Quality control

We can now look at the library size, the number of transcripts that were detected in all of the cells:

hist(colSums(counts(pbmc.sce)), breaks = 100, 
     xlab="#genes per cell", 
     main = "Genes per cell distribution")

Most of the cells have a low library size (number of detected genes per cell) and only a few outliers have a high transcriptomic activity, which is typical of scRNAseq.

The first steps of our analysis need some basic statistics such as library size per cell or the mitochondrial gene content. These metadata can be generated with the perCellQCMetrics function. The results will then be added to the colData (column-specific metadata) of the sce:

## various cell QC metrics 
meta.data <- perCellQCMetrics(pbmc.sce, 
                              subsets = list(Mito=grep("MT-", 
                                                       rowData(pbmc.sce)$Symbol)))

colData(pbmc.sce) <- cbind(colData(pbmc.sce), meta.data)

Overview of the pipeline

The analysis pipeline can be roughly divided into 3 parts -
pre-processing, dimensionality reduction and visualization, and differential analyses:

  1. Pre-processing
    • Quality control (QC) and filtering
    • Normalization
    • Selection of highly variable genes
    • Removing unwanted sources of variation
  2. Dimensionality reduction and visualization
    • Principal Component Analysis (PCA)
    • Clustering
    • tSNE
  3. Downstream analyses

Pre-processing

Pre-processing steps for scRNA-seq data include:

  • Filtering cells and/or genes based on quality control (QC) metrics
  • Data normalization and scaling
  • Selection of highly variable genes: these are the “interesting” genes that are used in downstream analyses
  • Removing unwanted sources of variation (if necessary)

Quality control (QC) and filtering

Filtering can be used to exclude cells or genes that do not meet QC metrics. A common filtering step is based on the total count for each cell and the mitochondrial content:

plot(pbmc.sce$sum, pbmc.sce$subsets_Mito_percent, pch = 20, 
     xlab = "# Genes per cell", 
     ylab = "% mitochondrial content")

We can first exclude cells with a clear outlier number of genes detected; these are assumed to be doublets or multiplets (two or more cells sequenced as a single cell) or debris of cells (resulting in low counts). We also filter cells based on the percentage of mitochondrial genes; a high percentage of mitochondrial genes usually indicate damages to the cell due to loss of cytoplasm.

For both metrics, the isOutlier function can be used to detect outliers cells based on the deviation to a median absolute value (MAD);

## outliers of detected genes
outliers.ngenes <- isOutlier(pbmc.sce$sum, type="both", log=TRUE)
table(outliers.ngenes)
## outliers.ngenes
## FALSE  TRUE 
##  2595   105
## Same for mitochondrial content
outliers.mito <- isOutlier(pbmc.sce$subsets_Mito_percent, type="higher", log=TRUE)
table(outliers.mito)
## outliers.mito
## FALSE  TRUE 
##  2686    14
outliers.sum <- ifelse(outliers.ngenes, ifelse(outliers.mito, "both", "n.genes"), ifelse(outliers.mito, "mito", "no") ) 

plot(pbmc.sce$sum, pbmc.sce$subsets_Mito_percent, pch = 20, 
     col = factor(outliers.sum), 
     xlab = "# Genes per cell", ylab = "% mitochondrial content")
legend("topright", legend = levels(factor(outliers.sum)), 
  col = 1:length(unique(outliers.sum)), 
  pch = 20, title = "outlier")

pbmc.sce <- pbmc.sce[,!(outliers.mito | outliers.ngenes)]
dim(pbmc.sce)
## [1] 32738  2587

Finally we can remove features that are not expressed in any cells:

feats.to.keep <- nexprs(pbmc.sce, byrow=TRUE) > 0
table(feats.to.keep)
## feats.to.keep
## FALSE  TRUE 
## 16247 16491
pbmc.sce <- pbmc.sce[feats.to.keep,]
dim(pbmc.sce)
## [1] 16491  2587

Of note, these filtering settings are rather arbitrary and simplistic: it is still an active field of research and many packages have been developed to this end.

Normalization and scaling

We use the normalization method logNormCounts, which normalizes the gene expression measurements for each cell by their size factor followed by a log-transformation (with an additional pseudo-count of 1 to handle zeros). Normalized data are stored in a new assay, logcounts (which can be accessed with a function of the same name).

# Normalization
pbmc.sce <- logNormCounts(pbmc.sce)
assayNames(pbmc.sce)
## [1] "counts"    "logcounts"
# access the assay
logcounts(pbmc.sce)[41:45,45:50]

Selection of highly variable genes

As many other processing packages, scran detects highly variable genes and focuses on these for the downstream analysis. This can be done with getTopHVGs. Here we will select the 2000 top variable genes:

# Find highly variable genes
dec <- modelGeneVar(pbmc.sce)
top.hvgs <- getTopHVGs(dec, n = 2000)
is.hvgs <- rownames(pbmc.sce) %in% top.hvgs + 1
plot(dec$mean, dec$total, xlab="Mean log-expression", ylab="Variance", col = is.hvgs, pch = 20)

Most scRNAseq data exhibits this mean-variance relationship (higher average expression is associated with higher variability up to a plateau) and getTopHVGs ranks the genes by accounting for this relationship.

Dimensionality reduction & visualization

Principal Component Analysis (PCA)

Next, we perform principal component analysis (PCA, linear dimensionality reduction) on the pre-processed data. For more accuracy, the PCA is performed on the HVGs that we identified in the previous section. The result can be accessed with reducedDim.

# PCA
pbmc.sce <- runPCA(pbmc.sce, subset_row = top.hvgs)
reducedDimNames(pbmc.sce)
## [1] "PCA"
head(reducedDim(pbmc.sce))[,1:3]
##                        PC1         PC2        PC3
## AAACATACAACCAC-1 -5.511639  -0.2553097  2.2678167
## AAACATTGAGCTAC-1 -2.079025   5.7537708 -5.2173622
## AAACATTGATCAGC-1 -4.004750  -2.0708380  3.0352766
## AAACCGTGCTTCCG-1 13.430830   1.8109118 -0.6837795
## AAACCGTGTATGCG-1  2.288813 -10.7617927 -8.0167221
## AAACGCACTGGTAC-1 -3.093118  -0.8845514  1.4957724
plotPCA(pbmc.sce)

Although PCA is often used for visualization purpose in other fields of research, its aim in scRNAseq is mainly to help clustering. Due to the non-linear nature of scRNAseq data, other methods of visualization are typically more effective (shown in the next sections).

Clustering

scran includes a graph-based clustering method. Cells are embedded in a graph structure - for example, a shared nearest neighbours (SNN) graph, based on the local density of points. The determination of neighbours generation of the graph is computed on the PCA reduction that we performed before.

cluster_fast_greedy runs the clustering using a greedy optimization of the modularity metric, which measures the connection density between the nodes of different clusters. Other graph construction and (many!) clustering methods exist (e.g., K nearest neighbors followed by walktrap) but we will use the former for this example:

g <- buildSNNGraph(pbmc.sce, use.dimred="PCA")
cluster <- igraph::cluster_fast_greedy(g)$membership
pbmc.sce$cluster <- factor(cluster)
table(pbmc.sce$cluster)
## 
##    1    2    3    4 
##  463 1160  326  638

t-SNE and UMAP

The ‘tSNE’ algorithm (nonlinear dimensionality reduction) is widely used to visualize single-cell RNA-seq and CyTOF datasets.

While PCA aims to preserve the variance in the data, tSNE is designed to maintain the neighborhood of data points. This facilitates 2-dimensional visualization of groups/clusters of cells with similar transcription profiles, which helps to identify cell populations. However, it can also be harder to interpret than PCA. This is because: (i) the tSNE dimensions do not have an underlying meaning, (ii) re-runs using different random seeds generate different plots, and (iii) only local distances on the plot are meaningful (i.e. two clusters that are “further away” are not necessarily more distinct).

‘UMAP’ (Uniform Manifold Approximation and Projection) is another non-linear dimensionality reduction technique. It has shown to improve tSNE in terms of runtime, consistency, meaningful organization of cell clusters and preservation of continuums.

# Run tSNE
set.seed(1234)
pbmc.sce <- runTSNE(pbmc.sce, 
  components = 2, ntop = 500, 
  exprs_values = "logcounts")

# Run UMAP
pbmc.sce <- runUMAP(pbmc.sce, 
  ncomponents = 2, ntop = 500, 
  exprs_values = "logcounts")

To plot the reduced dimensions single or multiplot layouts can be used. Any colData variable can be plotted aside defined by colour_by.

multiplot(cols = 2,
  plotTSNE(pbmc.sce, colour_by = "cluster") + 
    ggtitle("Tsne - (no global structure)"),
  plotUMAP(pbmc.sce, colour_by = "cluster") + 
    ggtitle("UMAP - (global structure)"))
## Warning: 'multiplot' is deprecated.
## Use 'gridExtra::grid.arrange' instead.
## See help("Deprecated")

Downstream analysis

Downstream analyses include a variety of steps to enable biological interpretation of the data:

  • Identify marker genes per cluster
  • Assigning celltypes by identifying marker genes, which distinguish cluster.
  • Differential expression analysis within the same celltypes, but different conditions (e.g. healthy vs. patient).
  • Data integration from different experiments/patients/batches.
  • Generating cell trajectories that represent cell differentiation processes from time-course experiments.

Marker gene identification

Here we show how to identify cluster-specific genes with the scran package using differential expression. These genes can be seen as “representative” genes that are ideally exclusively expressed in a subpopulation of cells (e.g. CD8 for CD8+ cytotoxic T lymphocytes).

By default, scran identifies positive and negative markers for a single cluster (function findMarkers, using the cluster argument to specify the vector of clusters), compared to all other cells. We also specify that we search for genes that are up-regulated (direction = "up") and differential between one cluster and all other groups (pval.type = "all").

Let’s first replace the rownames of the object with ‘human-readable’ names:

rownames(pbmc.sce) <- rowData(pbmc.sce)$Symbol
# Calculate marker genes:
# Find all markers for cluster 1
pbmc.markers <- findMarkers(pbmc.sce,
  groups = pbmc.sce$cluster,
  pval.type = "all",
  lfc = 1, 
  direction = "up")
# View markers for 4th cluster
head(pbmc.markers[[3]])
## DataFrame with 6 rows and 6 columns
##              p.value         FDR summary.logFC   logFC.1   logFC.2   logFC.4
##            <numeric>   <numeric>     <numeric> <numeric> <numeric> <numeric>
## CD79A    5.19623e-76 8.56911e-72       2.29616   2.30169   2.29616   2.29817
## CD74     1.38506e-74 1.14205e-70       1.98735   4.12280   3.72252   1.98735
## CD79B    1.51272e-54 8.31543e-51       1.95369   2.10459   2.01666   1.95369
## MS4A1    8.29797e-29 3.42104e-25       1.60377   1.60829   1.60836   1.60377
## HLA-DQA1 2.90305e-20 9.57483e-17       1.56393   1.94282   1.89753   1.56393
## HLA-DRA  2.92694e-18 8.04468e-15       1.51586   4.10534   4.04836   1.51586

We can now check the results by visualizing the markers’ expression compared to the other clusters. One approach is the violin plot:

# Visualize marker genes: expression of marker genes by cluster
top.markers <- rownames(pbmc.markers[[3]])[1:4]
# Violin plots
plotExpression(pbmc.sce, features =top.markers, x = "cluster", colour_by = "cluster")

Another approach is to visualize the marker genes expression on the T-SNE space:

# Feature plot
ps <- lapply(top.markers, function(g) plotTSNE(pbmc.sce, colour_by = g))
multiplot(cols = 4, plotlist = ps)
## Warning: 'multiplot' is deprecated.
## Use 'gridExtra::grid.arrange' instead.
## See help("Deprecated")

The 3 top markers, CCL5, NKG7 and IL32 are good markers for T-cells and NK cells so we can already hypothesize that we have these populations in clusters 1 and 3.

Cell type annotation

One way to annotate the data (i.e., retrieve the cell-types) can be done by examination of the marker genes previously identified. However, such annotations are hardly reproducible, manual and not scalable to bigger datasets.

We will here see one automatic method of annotation: the reference-based annotation. These types of methods assign a label to each cell of a query dataset based on its correlation with a well-curated reference sample where the cell-types are known. One popular tool using this approach is the singleR package.

Let’s first load a reference PBMC (blood) dataset:

ref <- BlueprintEncodeData() ## write 'yes' if asked to create a cache directory
## snapshotDate(): 2021-10-19
## see ?celldex and browseVignettes('celldex') for documentation
## loading from cache
## see ?celldex and browseVignettes('celldex') for documentation
## loading from cache
ref
## class: SummarizedExperiment 
## dim: 19859 259 
## metadata(0):
## assays(1): logcounts
## rownames(19859): TSPAN6 TNMD ... LINC00550 GIMAP1-GIMAP5
## rowData names(0):
## colnames(259): mature.neutrophil
##   CD14.positive..CD16.negative.classical.monocyte ...
##   epithelial.cell.of.umbilical.artery.1
##   dermis.lymphatic.vessel.endothelial.cell.1
## colData names(3): label.main label.fine label.ont

We can now call the SingleR function, which will compute the Spearman rank correlation for each cell in the query against the reference dataset and return the most probable label:

pred <- SingleR(test=pbmc.sce, ref=ref, labels=ref$label.main)
table(pred$labels)
## 
##      B-cells CD4+ T-cells CD8+ T-cells          HSC    Monocytes     NK cells 
##          326          540          872            6          643          200

We can then inspect the results in a heatmap:

plotScoreHeatmap(pred)

We can see that SingleR could identify the NK cells, B cells and monocytes with a high confidence. However CD8+ and CD4+ T cells scores are overlapping, which is a common problem in annotation as these two cell-types differentiate quite late in the lymphoid lineage.

We can also visualize the predictions on a TSNE:

pbmc.sce$singler.label <- pred$labels
plotTSNE(pbmc.sce, colour_by = "singler.label") + 
    ggtitle("SingleR reference-based annotation")

As we hypothesized previously, clusters 1 and 3 contain mainly lymphocytes T and NK cells.
